We begin by looking at the very first terminal, t136, which occurs at position 1 of the input.  In the grammar the only nonterminal that ever produces t136 is

Hence any successful parse of the whole string must have, at position 1, NT72.  But the start symbol S has only two productions

  S → NT19 NT42  
  S → NT41 NT26

so whatever nonterminal covers the first token must appear as the *left* child in one of those two productions.  In other words, in a successful CYK parse one of

 (1) NT19 ⇒* [t136 …]  
 (2) NT41 ⇒* [t136 …]

must hold.  But neither NT19 nor NT41 can ever generate t136 in their leftmost derivation:

– NT19 has the sole binary rule NT19 → NT14 NT29, and neither NT14 nor NT29 (and no further chain of binary rules) can begin by producing t136.  
– NT41 has binary rules NT41 → NT60 NT82 or NT41 → NT34 NT41 (and also NT41 → 't161'), and again neither NT60 nor NT34 (nor NT41 itself) can derive t136 in their leftmost position.

Since the first symbol t136 can only come from NT72 and NT72 cannot appear as the left half of an S‐production, no complete derivation from S is possible. Therefore the grammar does **not** generate the string.
